    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Understanding Electoral Apportionment</h2>
      <p>The <strong>list of electoral votes by state highest to lowest</strong> is more than just numbers; it is the fundamental architecture of American presidential elections. Under the United States Constitution, the president is not elected directly by the national popular vote. Instead, an intermediary body known as the Electoral College determines the outcome. Every four years, these designated electors cast the decisive ballots for the presidency.</p>

      <p>The total number of electoral votes is fixed at 538. This number is derived from the total membership of Congress: 435 Representatives, 100 Senators, and 3 specific electoral votes allocated to the District of Columbia by the 23rd Amendment. For a candidate to secure the presidency, they must win a pure majority, which means reaching the critical threshold of 270 electoral votes.</p>

      <p>The allocation you see below is directly tied to the 2020 United States Census. The Constitution mandates a decennial census to count the population and reapportion the 435 House seats among the 50 states accordingly. Because every state automatically receives exactly two Senators, the minimum number of electoral votes any state can hold is three. States with massive, rapidly growing populations command the largest share of electoral power, making them central targets in modern political campaigns.</p>

      <p>Following the 2020 census, significant demographic shifts resulted in the reallocation of several electoral votes. Texas, reflecting rapid population growth, gained two votes. Florida, North Carolina, Colorado, Oregon, and Montana each gained one. Conversely, slow-growing or population-losing states like California, New York, Illinois, Michigan, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and West Virginia all saw a reduction in their electoral count.</p>

      <p>This dynamic shifting of power highlights the crucial importance of the decennial census. It also underscores why campaign strategies continuously evolve, shifting focus toward growing sunbelt states while fiercely defending the traditional rust belt battlegrounds. The table below provides the definitive distribution of this power, sortable by vote count, population, and recent changes.</p>
    </div>

