    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How many electoral votes does each state get?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Each state's electoral votes equal its total number of Senators and Representatives in Congress. Every state gets exactly two Senators, plus a number of Representatives based on its population size determined by the decennial census.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What state has the most electoral votes?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">California currently has the most electoral votes, holding 54 votes. This allocation is effective for the 2024 and 2028 presidential elections, representing a loss of one vote compared to its previous count of 55.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What happens if a state loses electoral votes?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">When a state loses electoral votes after a census, it means its population growth was slower compared to other states. This triggers congressional redistricting, where the state must redraw its district maps to account for the reduced number of House seats.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How many electoral votes are needed to win the presidency?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">A candidate must secure an absolute majority of the Electoral College to win the presidency. With a total of 538 electoral votes available, the magic number required to win is 270 electoral votes.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Which states have 3 electoral votes?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The states with the minimum 3 electoral votes are Alaska, Delaware, North Dakota, South Dakota, Vermont, and Wyoming. The District of Columbia also has 3 electoral votes under the 23rd Amendment.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
